00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:46.880
without gluten really gets at
the core of the issue in thinking

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:48.162
about elasticity and cooking.

00:03:48.162 --> 00:03:50.870
And that's because as we will tell
you and as Mark will tell you,

00:03:50.870 --> 00:03:54.810
gluten is a protein
or really two proteins

00:03:54.810 --> 00:04:00.070
which are the core elastic element
in making baked goods and pasta.

00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:03.640
And when you ask yourself, how do
I recreate a dish without using it,

00:04:03.640 --> 00:04:05.890
then you've basically thrown
it all out of the window.

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:09.098
And you have to really figure out what
you're doing when you put it together,

00:04:09.098 --> 00:04:12.154
which is the intellectual issue that
I think underlies this lecture, yes?

00:04:12.154 --> 00:04:12.820
Well, we'll see.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:13.380
MARK LADNER: Yes.

00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:13.870
MICHAEL BRENNER: I
haven't heard the lecture.

00:04:13.870 --> 00:04:15.286
MARK LADNER: Partially, partially.

00:04:15.286 --> 00:04:17.410
MICHAEL BRENNER: Partially.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:19.390
But the thing is that
controlling elasticity

00:04:19.390 --> 00:04:21.110
is central to all of cooking.

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:24.290
And just to throw up some more
examples for you to think about,

00:04:24.290 --> 00:04:28.860
you all know that some of you like
steak very well-done and some of you

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:30.310
like it not so well-done.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.720
And what many of you
might know is what people

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:35.230
call the thumb test, which is
that if you're cooking a steak

00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:37.930
and you want to find out how
well-done it is, what you do

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:38.990
is you just push on it.

00:04:38.990 --> 00:04:41.346
And If it's really squishy,
then it's not very well-done

00:04:41.346 --> 00:04:43.470
and if it's not very squishy,
then it is well-done.

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:45.344
Well, that's a measurement
that you're making

00:04:45.344 --> 00:04:49.760
with your hand of the elasticity
of the steak, which you're

00:04:49.760 --> 00:04:53.110
doing which changes as a function of
the temperature inside of the steak,

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:55.900
because there are transitions in
the proteins in the steak that

00:04:55.900 --> 00:04:58.750
cause it to firm up.

00:04:58.750 --> 00:05:02.337
So the same issue occurs with cheeses.

00:05:02.337 --> 00:05:04.170
And so the question is
how to quantify that.

00:05:04.170 --> 00:05:09.080
And this, as you know, for better or
for worst-- well, I'm a scientist.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:09.900
Pia is a scientist.

00:05:09.900 --> 00:05:13.290
We're scientists and so we
basically ruin everything.

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:16.150
Well, you don't ruin everything
but I ruin everything.

00:05:16.150 --> 00:05:20.340
And so instead of this beautiful cheese
and you should squish on the cheese

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:24.220
or you can squish on the
steak, we think about springs.

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:27.100
And the thing is if you squish on
the spring, it's the same thing.

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:29.670
You have to push on
it and it reacts back.

00:05:29.670 --> 00:05:31.614
How many of you have
taken a physics class?

00:05:31.614 --> 00:05:33.530
And remember, they told
you about these things

00:05:33.530 --> 00:05:35.530
and you thought it was the worst
thing that ever happened to you.

00:05:35.530 --> 00:05:38.560
But the thing is that really,
if you think about cooking tofu,

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:39.560
it's just like a spring.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:43.410
If you squish on soft tofu, then it's
squishy and firm tofu isn't so squishy.

00:05:43.410 --> 00:05:46.700
So you're just measuring the
spring constant of a spring.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.250
And in fact, the way I think of
a steak-- this is sort of a joke

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:52.740
but it's not totally wrong--
is that a steak basically

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:54.820
is just a network of springs.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:56.950
And if you imagine it
as a network of springs,

00:05:56.950 --> 00:05:59.980
the most important parameter
in the network of springs

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:02.429
is the bond length, the
length between the springs,

00:06:02.429 --> 00:06:03.720
because they're little springs.

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:04.511
You can't see them.

00:06:04.511 --> 00:06:05.660
This is a cartoons thing.

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:09.950
And so anyway, in honor of that,
the equation of the week this week

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:11.200
is the following.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:14.190
It's this number e, which scientists
call the elastic modulus, which

00:06:14.190 --> 00:06:16.120
measures how squishy something is.

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:20.200
And it's equal to some energy over
l cubed, where l is the bond length.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:21.506
So you all have to clap--

00:06:21.506 --> 00:06:24.170
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:25.920
--because that's the
equation of the week.

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:27.970
And the amazing thing
about this equation

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:31.290
is that it can be used to think
about the elasticity in foods

00:06:31.290 --> 00:06:36.350
as diverse as steak, tofu,
pasta, pretty much anything,

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:37.760
cake, whatever you'd like.

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:41.220
And the reason that things
are more or less elastic

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:42.860
is there are really only two options.

00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.990
You either increase u, which
is how strong the bonds are,

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:49.040
or you decrease l, which is
how small the springs are.

00:06:49.040 --> 00:06:50.860
And those are the two
options you've got.

00:06:50.860 --> 00:06:53.069
And so at least when I listen
to Mark-- actually when

00:06:53.069 --> 00:06:54.860
I'm about to listen to
Mark, what I'm going

00:06:54.860 --> 00:06:57.922
to be thinking to myself among other
things is, how is he controlling u?

00:06:57.922 --> 00:06:59.630
How is he controlling
the bond strengths?

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:01.540
How is he controlling the
distance between the bonds?

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:02.970
And that's really the issue.

00:07:02.970 --> 00:07:05.990
